  "prompt": "Which is best book for machine learning?",
  "response": "There isn't a single \"best\" book for machine learning, as the ideal book often depends on your background, interests, and learning style. However, here are some highly regarded books in the field of machine learning:\n\n1. **\"Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning\" by Christopher Bishop**: This book is comprehensive and covers a wide range of topics in machine learning. It is particularly well-regarded for its clear explanations and useful illustrations.\n\n2. **\"Machine Learning: A Probabilistic Perspective\" by Kevin P. Murphy**: This book provides a thorough introduction to the field from a probabilistic viewpoint. It's well-suited for those who have a strong mathematical background.\n\n3. **\"Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow\" by Aur\u00e9lien G\u00e9ron**: This practical guide is great for beginners and intermediate learners who want to get hands-on experience with popular machine learning libraries.\n\n4. **\"Deep Learning\" by Ian Goodfellow, Yoshua Bengio, and Aaron Courville**: This book is considered the definitive textbook on deep learning. It's suitable for those who already have a good understanding of machine learning fundamentals.\n\n5. **\"The Hundred-Page Machine Learning Book\" by Andriy Burkov**: This concise book aims to provide a quick yet comprehensive overview of machine learning concepts, making it a good starting point for beginners.\n\n6. **\"Machine Learning Yearning\" by Andrew Ng**: Though not a traditional textbook, this book offers valuable insights into practical aspects of building machine learning systems and is written by one of the leading figures in the field.\n\nSelecting the best book for you will depend on your current level of expertise and what you hope to achieve. If you're new to the field, starting with more practical guides like Aur\u00e9lien G\u00e9ron's book might be beneficial, while more advanced readers might prefer Murphy's or Goodfellow's texts.",
